hether the HR function is changing to become an effective strategic partner. It also analyzes how organizations can more effectively manage their human capital. The present study compares data from earlier studies to data collected in 2004. The results show some important changes and indicate what HR needs to do to be effective. Practices are identified that enable HR functions to be high value-added strategic partners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aOrganizational effectiveness. 0aPersonnel management. 4aBusiness -- Human Resources. 4aBusiness -- Management and Leadership. 4aBusiness -- Strategy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Human Resources & Personnel Management.2bisacsh1 aBoudreau, John W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMohrman, Susan Albers, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNeilson, Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOsganian, Nora, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476795840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767958/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles